    "reasoning": "To implement an 8-bit positive edge detector, we need to compare the current input value with the input value from the previous clock cycle. A positive edge is defined as a transition from 0 to 1. In terms of bitwise logic, for each bit $i$, the edge occurs if $in[i] == 1$ and $prev_in[i] == 0$. This is equivalent to the logical operation: $pedge[i] = in[i] \text{ AND (NOT } prev_in[i])$. \n\nSteps:\n1. Define a register `prev_in` of 8 bits to store the state of the input from the previous cycle.\n2. Use a sequential `always @(posedge clk)` block to update `prev_in` with the current value of `in` on every clock edge.\n3. Use a combinational `assign` statement to calculate `pedge` as `in & ~prev_in`.\n4. Note: The specification says 'The output bit should be set the cycle after a 0 to 1 transition occurs'. If the transition happens at cycle $T$, `prev_in` captures the 0 and `in` captures the 1. The logic `in & ~prev_in` will evaluate to 1 at cycle $T+1$ relative to the start of the transition, which matches the requirement of being 'the cycle after'.\n\nAdvice to avoid syntax errors:\n- Ensure the port widths match the specification (8 bits for `in` and `pedge`).\n- Ensure all ports are declared with the correct direction and type (`logic`).\n- Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic to avoid sensitivity list errors.\n- Avoid using `reg` for combinational assignments in SystemVerilog; use `logic` instead.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic       clk,\n    input  logic [7:0] in,\n    output logic [7:0] pedge\n);\n\n    // Register to store the previous state of the input\n    logic [7:0] prev_in;\n\n    // Initialize prev_in to avoid starting with X\n    initial begin\n        prev_in = 8'b0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic to update the previous state\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        prev_in <= in;\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic to detect 0 -> 1 transition\n    // pedge is high when current bit is 1 and previous bit was 0\n    assign pedge = in & (~prev_in);\n\nendmodule"
